messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path:

- All HTTP methods acceptable:
  false

- POST:
  true

- OPTIONS:
  false

- TRACE:
  false

- GET:
  false

- PUT:
  false

- DELETE:
  false

- PATCH:
  false

Explanation:
- The controller class has no class-level @RequestMapping, so there is no prefix; the endpoint path is exactly the value in the method-level annotation: @RequestMapping(value = "/printdocument/{id}/budget", ...). The {id} path parameter is present and mapped to a long in the method signature.
- The method explicitly declares method = RequestMethod.POST, so only POST is allowed according to the source code. Because the code restricts the mapping to POST, "all methods" is false and other specific methods (GET, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, OPTIONS, TRACE, HEAD) are not accepted per the annotations alone. (This answer is based solely on the code annotations and signatures, not on any runtime framework behaviors such as implicit HEAD/OPTIONS handling.)
